a “racial democracy,” a uniquely harmonious mix of races and cultures. While the experiences of Brazilian policymakers and diplomats in Africa reflected the logic of racial democracy, they also exposed ruptures in this interpretation of Brazilian identity. Did Brazil share a “lusotropical” identity with Portugal and its African colonies, so that it was bound to support Portuguese colonialism at the expense of Brazil’s ties with African nations? Or was Brazil a country of “Africans of every color,” compelled to support decolonization in its role as a natural leader in the South Atlantic? Drawing on interviews with retired Brazilian diplomats and intellectuals, Dávila shows the Brazilian belief in racial democracy to be about not only race but also Portuguese ethnicity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393443.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles